imply that the pathway in its conserved form is important for the fitness of those species.<\/p>\n\n<p>For some examples, here is a page on evolutionary conserved pathways in Drosophila: <a href=\"http://www.sdbonline.org/sites/fly/aimain/aadevinx.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.sdbonline.org/sites/fly/aimain/aadevinx.htm<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":16301,"question_id":16300,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1396446007}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16300/what-does-it-mean-for-a-chemical-pathway-to-be-conserved","last_activity_date":1396446007,"creation_date":1396444045,"answer_count":1,"title":"What does it mean for a chemical pathway to be conserved?","body":"<p>In many papers the MAPK pathway, (along with many others) is referred to as being conserved: <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www3.aiche.org/Proceedings/Abstract.aspx?PaperID=133783\" rel=\"nofollow\">Example<\/a>: \"The mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK) cascades are ubiquitous in eukaryotic signal transduction, and these pathways are conserved in cells from yeast to mammals\"<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hippo_signaling_pathway\" rel=\"nofollow\">example 2<\/a> \"The Hippo signaling pathway appears to be highly conserved.\"<\/p>\n\n<p>What does it mean for a pathway to be conserved?<\/p>\n","question_id":16300,"tags":["cell-biology"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":16301,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":582,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1396444812},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/faeeef7d7a44f1007f2832d54f8e7e94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1005,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1005/everyone","reputation":1798,"display_name":"Everyone","accept_rate":57},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe76a1ad06a1b64a47d4ededd9c084bf?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":744,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/744/p