a0b5ae88?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3029,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3029/bpeter","reputation":94,"display_name":"bpeter"},"score":0,"post_id":16294,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"edited":false,"creation_date":1396463616,"comment_id":21995,"body":"this should be true for a diploid population. The additive genetic variance is defined as the variance in a population where there are no interaction effects between genotypes, so $w_{ij}$ can be written as $w_iw_j$"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":16294,"edited":false,"creation_date":1396513049,"comment_id":22006,"body":"I&#39;m sorry I might be a bit slow to understand :)\u2026 Can you please show the development to find back $\\sigma_A^2 = 2x(1-x)(xW_{11}+(1-2x)W_{12} - (1-x)W_{22})^2$ from your equations? Thank you."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1396410406,"creation_date":1396410406,"body":"<p>Well, the total genetic variance is just, by the definition of the variance,\n$$\n\\sigma^2 =\\sum_{i,j} f_i f_j (w_{ij}-\\bar{w})^2\n$$\n(using $f_i$ and $w_{ij}$ for frequency and fitness, respectively), and\n$$\\bar{w} = \\sum_{i,j} f_i f_j w_{ij}$$ is just the average fitness.<\/p>\n\n<p>You can calculate the additive genetic variance for different loci by simply assuming that there is no dominance effect, i.e. the alleles are independent. If it helps, think of it as a quantitative trait in a haploid organism. Thus,<\/p>\n\n<p>$$\n\\sigma^2_A =\\sum_{i,j} f_i f_j (w_iw_j-\\bar{w}')^2 = \\sum_i f_i(w_i-\\bar{w}')^2.\n$$\nwith \n$$\nf_i=\\sum_jf_{ij};  w_i=\\sum_j f_{ij}w_{ij}; \\bar{w}' = \\sum_i f_i w_i; \n$$<\/p>\n","answer_id":16294,"question_id":16248,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16248/additive-genetic-variance-with-n-alleles","last_activity_date":1396410406,"creation_date":1396261559,"answer_count":1,"title":"Additive genetic variance with $n$ alleles","body":"<p>The genetic variance of a quantitative trait (the quantitative trait in question is fitness) can be express as the sum of two components, the dominance and additive variance:<\/p>\n\n<p>$$\\sigma_D^2 + \\sigma_A^2  = \\sigma^2$$<\/p>\n\n<p>, where $\\sigma$ is the genetic variance, $\\sigma_D^2$ is the dominance variance and $\\sigma_A^2$ is the additive variance. $\\sigma_D^2$  and $\\sigma_A^2$ are given by<\/p>\n\n<p>$$\\sigma_D^2 = x^2(1-x)^2(2\\cdot W_{12} - W_{11} - W_{22})^2$$<\/p>\n\n<p>$$\\sigma_A^2 = 2x(1-x)(xW_{11}+(1-2x)W_{12} - (1-x)W_{22})^2$$<\/p>\n\n<p>, where $W_{11}$, $W_{12}$ and $W_{22}$ are the fitness of the three possible genotypes and $x$ and $1-x$ give the allele frequencies.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Question<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>The above definition makes sense for one bi-allelic locus.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>How are $\\sigma_D^2$, $\\sigma_A^2$ and $\\sigma^2$ defined for a locus that have $n$ alleles?<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16249/additive-genetic-variance-with-n-loci\">Here<\/a> is a related question<\/p>\n","question_id":16248,"tags":["evolution","mathematical-models","natural-selection","population-dynamics","population-biology"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":16294,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":116,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5cff3e84bcedd40163c74d33b827ac7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/307/lancelafontaine","reputation":3814,"display_name":"LanceLafontaine","accept_rate":47},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/66c66c4d97a7bc3859a85253f003e1fb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"moderator","user_id":6,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6/mad-scientist","reputation":6781,"display_name":"Mad Scientist","accept_rate":55},"score":2,"post_id":16284,"edited":false,"creation_date":1396383672,"comment_id":21955,"body":"I&#39;d assume that you use different antibiotic resistances for selection, that way you should be able to ensure that both plasmid are taken up successfully."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":16284,"edited":false,"creation_date":1396384772,"comment_id":21956,"body":"you do, but some will maintain both plasmids, so the two antiobitics on the plate still should give you want you want."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2550aa98332616362fa07d023da45d40?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":28,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/28/gergana-vandova","reputation":5081,"display_name":"Gergana Vandova","accept_rate":35},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1396385788,"creation_date":1396385788,"body":"<p>If the plasmids you wish to transform are very big (more than 20kb), the co-transformation might not be very efficient (you might not get any colonies). Electroporation should work though, as electrocompetent cells are more efficient than chemically competent cells. Alternatively, as you have read, you could transform your first plasmid and select for it, and then make these cell that harbor it competent and transform the second plasmid. As long as you select for the plasmids (with kan/carb/etc resistance marker), the cells that grow on the selective media will keep both of them. If I were you, I would try the co-transformation and then if it doesn't work I would do the sequential transformation.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16286,"question_id":16284,"up_vote_count":4}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16284/is-a-sequential-double-transformation-acceptable","last_activity_date":1396385788,"creation_date":1396383347,"answer_count":1,"title":"Is a sequential double transformation acceptable?","body":"<p>Standard protocol states having two compatible vectors being transformed simultaneously during the same procedure. I've come across a situation in which transforming one vector, obtaining results, and then transforming the other is preferable. <strong>Is there any reason to think that this wouldn't work? Do I risk losing my first vector upon transformation of the second?<\/strong><\/p>\n","question_id":16284,"tags":["microbiology","protocol","plasmids"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":223,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ba0c3e8ef54e736e6bbbef2877184756?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4440,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4440/kieran-cooney","reputation":168,"display_name":"Kieran Cooney"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/o26hX.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6224,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6224/joce","reputation":608,"display_name":"Joce"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1396385314,"creation_date":1396385314,"body":"<p>Pavement cells should content you:\n<img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/SzRon.gif\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>From <a href=\"http://dev.biologists.org/content/131/21/5215.full\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://dev.biologists.org/content/131/21/5215.full<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":16285,"question_id":10982,"up_vote_count":1}],"link