ism is better than others, not even human.<\/p>\n\n<p>New functions are not created just like that, because a species need it. To take your cephalopod's example : if there's pressure from predators, they won't simply grow spikes in order to protect themselves. However, if mutations (one or many) appear in the DNA sequence that make spikes instead of, say, skin, then this particular cephalopod will have better chances of surviving than others and so, better chances to reproduce and pass his new genes.<\/p>\n\n<p>Mutations do not necessarily imply degradation -just as the los of one function is not necessarily a degradation. Every organs appeared thanks to mutations and / or duplications. For example, the humans' ability to see colors is due to 3 types of pigments (blue, red, green) named opsine S (blue), opsine M (green), opsine L (red). You add rhodopsine which is sensible to light to see clearly. If you study a mouse's eye, you'll only find 2 opsines + rhodophsine. Scientists have been able to recreate evolution's story : you start with an ancestral gene for opsine. The gene is duplicated and the copy is translocated on another chromosome. You now have 2 copies of the gene on 2 different chromosomes. They both mutate as mutations occur all of the time. You end up with 2 new genes. Then, duplication will happen again (no particular reason). You now have 4 genes, identical two by two. Three genes stay where they are, one of them is translocated on another chromosome and they'll all mutate. You finally get 4 genes on 3 different chromosomes (opsine M, L, S and rhodopsine). New genes and new ability appeared thanks to mutation, duplication and translocation. It just took millions of years of evolution and probably an impressive amount of tests. <\/p>\n\n<p>As Shigeta wrote, everything potentially exists. Some of the possibilities have been discovered, some have not. Evolution applies on hundreds millions of years and billions of living organisms and it process accidents after accidents. If what appears is selected, it stays, if not, it disappears.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16112,"question_id":16106,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1395872344},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4fd20b85d98a142f6c2f47ab7fd9bfb0?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6131,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6131/adamwong246","reputation":261,"display_name":"adamwong246"},"score":10,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2c33b5588bbd268ce2680853ea79b1a9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":231,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/231/mgkrebbs","reputation":3086,"display_name":"mgkrebbs"},"score":3,"post_id":16114,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395860085,"comment_id":21635,"body":"<i>The Blind Watchmaker<\/i> would be a good book to read, probably better than <i>The Selfish Gene<\/i>.  In any case, skip <i>The Extended Phenotype<\/i> until you are well acquainted with biology and evolution."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/412efaafb7affe9c6667543f58de948c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5502,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5502/lotusbiology","reputation":38,"display_name":"LotusBiology"},"score":0,"post_id":16114,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395861150,"comment_id":21639,"body":"&quot;a mutation will confer an advantage, rather than an disadvantage.&quot; Sure. But it will only confer an advantage in a horizontal way. In other words, it&#39;s just a variation on what was already there, not a new trait or morphology that will advance us from microbes to man. Which is what I was looking for as far as explanation. Also, what is the physical process that reads, understands and implements these changes and additions of new abilities? What is evolution&#39;s central processing unit?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4fd20b85d98a142f6c2f47ab7fd9bfb0?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6131,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6131/adamwong246","reputation":261,"display_name":"adamwong246"},"score":1,"post_id":16114,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395861910,"comment_id":21642,"body":"This is no such thing as a &quot;horizontal&quot; advantage. Every mutation is a subtle tweak which may or may not have benefits. The evolutionary process is a steady procession of such small changes. There is no single process which can be said to comprehend evolutionary changes, other than the ordinary processing of DNA within the cell. And evolution certainly has no CPU. Evolution is a distributed, emergent phenomenon. In no way is the process analogous to a computer.   I highly suggest you step back, do some real research and reevaluate your premises."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4fd20b85d98a142f6c2f47ab7fd9bfb0?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6131,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6131/adamwong246","reputation":261,"display_name":"adamwong246"},"score":0,"post_id":16114,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395862660,"comment_id":21644,"body":"Consider also <i>The Magic of Reality.<\/i> It is an introduction to science itself. <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/The-Magic-Reality-Whats-Really/dp/1451675046\" rel=\"nofollow\">amazon.com/The-Magic-Reality-Whats-Really/dp/1451675046<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/412efaafb7affe9c6667543f58de948c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5502,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5502/lotusbiology","reputation":38,"display_name":"LotusBiology"},"score":0,"post_id":16114,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395866717,"comment_id":21646,"body":"@AdamWong Let me explain what horizontal means there. It&#39;s known as horizontal evolution, where you have evolution that happens with breeding. To get from microbes to man, we need vertical evolution. Where we advance up in complexity and changes in kinds of species, rather than variation within kinds."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/412efaafb7affe9c6667543f58de948c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5502,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5502/lotusbiology","reputation":38,"display_name":"LotusBiology"},"score":0,"post_id":16114,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395866944,"comment_id":21647,"body":"&quot;In no way is the process analogous to a computer&quot;. Well, I don&#39;t know how else to explain what I&#39;m looking for. When you build something, it works like a computer. You have an input, processing, then output. To get our vertical evolution, you need an input of new instructions, physical mechanisms to understand the instruction and PHYSICALLY implement it, and output the new ability or morphology. How is that done in evolution? Where does the new information come from, and what in nature physically implements this new information?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/412efaafb7affe9c6667543f58de948c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5502,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5502/lotusbiology","reputation":38,"display_name":"LotusBiology"},"score":0,"post_id":16114,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395867254,"comment_id":21648,"body":"@ADAMWONG Let me give you another example besides the computer. To build something you need an Input/Output system. Take ants. When they want to build an ant mound for the queen. They already have this knowledge of how to build it, its innate. They then set out physically implementing this knowledge by gathering dirt and transporting it to the mound site. Eventually the mound is build which is the finished output. How does Evolution do that with organisms? New information, what reads it, and tells the genes 10 spikes, 1 inch apart, 5 inches up, and physically implements this morphology?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4fd20b85d98a142f6c2f47ab7fd9bfb0?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6131,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6131/adamwong246","reputation":261,"display_name":"adamwong246"},"score":3,"post_id":16114,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395873358,"comment_id":21678,"body":"To answer your first question, your notion of horizontal vs vertical evolution is unfounded. There is no such thing- mutations are small, though their effects may be outstanding. But very large changes, (ie microbes to men) are merely the accumulation of smaller changes."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4fd20b85d98a142f6c2f47ab7fd9bfb0?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6131,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6131/adamwong246","reputation":261,"display_name":"adamwong246"},"score":0,"post_id":16114,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395873515,"comment_id":21679,"body":"To answer your second question, <i>I suppose<\/i> the new information could said to be in the form of mutations and <i>I suppose<\/i> evolution can be said to implement that information in DNA. But that is projecting agency into a system which has none, so I would not use those terms."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4fd20b85d98a142f6c2f47ab7fd9bfb0?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6131,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6131/adamwong246","reputation":261,"display_name":"adamwong246"},"score":4,"post_id":16114,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395873889,"comment_id":21681,"body":"To answer your 3rd comment, the mapping of genotypes (information) to phenotypes (characteristics) is complicated. Genes are not instructions like &quot;Make the flamingo this precise shade of pink.&quot; Genes are instructions for creating proteins which eventually define the characteristics of the organism. (This explanation of gene expression is greatly simplified) In the same way, ants do not &quot;know&quot; how to build ant hills. They are parts within a larger machine (the ant colony) from which complicated behavior (ant hill building) emerge.  Read this: <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emergence\" rel=\"nofollow\">emergence<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bd4f0d39f82be9c22f6f01c80d7ad800?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6167,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6167/neil-slater","reputation":311,"display_name":"Neil Slater"},"score":0,"post_id":16114,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/412efaafb7affe9c6667543f58de948c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5502,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5502/lotusbiology","reputation":38,"display_name":"LotusBiology"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1395941985,"comment_id":21754,"body":"@LotusBiology: I almost wrote the same as adamwong246 just now. But one very accessible area (and I think quite amazing/beautiful) to help understand your question is introductions to Hox genes: see <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hox_gene\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hox_gene<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/412efaafb7affe9c6667543f58de948c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5502,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5502/lotusbiology","reputation":38,"display_name":"LotusBiology"},"score":0,"post_id":16114,"edited":false,"creation_date":1396008564,"comment_id":21784,"body":"&quot;Genes are not instructions like &quot;Make the flamingo this precise shade of pink.&quot; What does do that then?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/otBg3.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6151,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6151/richard-tingle","reputation":161,"display_name":"Richard Tingle"},"score":0,"post_id":16114,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/412efaafb7affe9c6667543f58de948c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5502,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5502/lotusbiology","reputation":38,"display_name":"LotusBiology"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1396014905,"comment_id":21797,"body":"@LotusBiology The shade of pink or the ant hill is <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emergence\" rel=\"nofollow\">emergent behaviour<\/a>; simple rules leading to a complex outcome. Much like evolution itself"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1395853476,"creation_date":1395853476,"body":"<p>You question, I'm afraid, betrays a deep misunderstanding of evolution. <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Genetic mutation is just errors in replication. So it creates nothing. It simply degrades.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>This is patently false. The vast majority of mutations are \"errors\", in that they produce a less fit organism. But once in a while, a mutation will confer an advantage, rather than an disadvantage. This, I suppose, is where \"new information\" comes from, though I would not use those terms. Your metaphor with software is not very accurate. If you want to \"evolve\" a piece of software through evolution, you do not insert new functionality into the source code. Instead, you would make a number of copies of the source code, each with a small, random alteration. Then you make the software available to all. The version that is most highly used on the market is then taken and the process is repeated. But good software is not developed in this way, for reasons that I hope are obvious. <\/p>\n\n<p>I would highly recommend reading \"The Selfish Gene\" or \"The Extended Phenotype\" by Richard Dawkins. <\/p>\n","answer_id":16114,"question_id":16106,"up_vote_count":10},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":11,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb576b29171a8396bf8acdb680c7e08?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6165,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6165/mcv","reputation":121,"display_name":"mcv"},"score":0,"post_id":16119,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395916119,"comment_id":21710,"body":"The computer analogy might work better if you look at machine code. Every combination of zeros and ones means something. Change one bit, and maybe a bit of data changes, maybe something gets stored in a different register, or maybe a different instruction gets called. It might end up doing that makes no sense, it might throw an error, or, just maybe, it does something that means meaningful. Still not a perfect analogy by a long shot though, and it&#39;s certainly not how genetic programming is generally implemented."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/v5upF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3624,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3624/fileunderwater","reputation":10502,"display_name":"fileunderwater"},"score":0,"post_id":16119,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395930718,"comment_id":21731,"body":"Nice answer. I would like to add that the last remark &quot;<i>Say I&#39;m a cephalopod...<\/i>&quot; contains two further erroneous assumptions. First, it seems assume that individuals evolve - only lineages/populations evolve. Second, it is implying &quot;guided&quot; evolution (I have this problem; with what instructions can that be solved?), ignoring that evolution is a trial and error process."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/412efaafb7affe9c6667543f58de948c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5502,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5502/lotusbiology","reputation":38,"display_name":"LotusBiology"},"score":0,"post_id":16119,"edited":false,"creation_date":1396010716,"comment_id":21792,"body":"@TERDON &quot;First of all, there is no such thing as &quot;correct&quot; or &quot;error&quot;,&quot; That&#39;s interesting you say this, cause MCV said below that Mutation introduces random errors. So  you say there is no such thing as error, and MCV is saying that mutations are errors, or at least introduces random errors."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":0,"post_id":16119,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/412efaafb7affe9c6667543f58de948c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5502,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5502/lotusbiology","reputation":38,"display_name":"LotusBiology"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1396015898,"comment_id":21798,"body":"@LotusBiology so? We are two different people giving different answers, what&#39;s your point? Anyway, while there are errors at the <i>cellular<\/i> level, where the copied DNA is not identical to the template, there are no &quot;errors&quot; in the evolutionary level. The term carries a certain implication and it was that implication I wanted to avoid. As far as evolution is concerned, there are no errors, only changes."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1395913393,"creation_date":1395870675,"body":"<p>Your basic problem is indeed a fundamental misunderstanding of how DNA and by extension its evolution works. First of all, there is no such thing as \"correct\" or \"error\", there are only changes, some of them are better for the individual and some are worse. You also have a basic misunderstanding of the concept of information. An error does not decrease the amount of information, it just alters that information. For example, consider this sentence:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The book is read<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Say, I make a simple error when I transcribe it:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The book is red<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The two statements contain the same amount of information. Nothing has been lost, only changed. <strong>But that change created new information<\/strong>. Now what if a try a different change:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The book is rled<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Now, this one is nonsensical, indeed, but how does that translate into DNA?<\/p>\n\n<p>The computer analogy is a bad one. Programming languages have a very specific set of rules and anything outside those rules results in a error. For example, while this is a perfectly valid statement in many scripting languages:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>print \"Hello World\"\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This one is not:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>priint \"Hello World\"\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>That, however, is not the way that DNA works. DNA is read in words of three characters, the codons. Every single possible \ncombination of those characters actually has a meaning. Therefore, a mutation like that above which would decrease the information content of the sentence (here, the gene) is not possible. Lets quantify. The DNA sequence consists of a long series of chemicals, commonly known as A, C, T and G. Since these are read in \"words\" of three \"letters\", this means you have:<\/p>\n\n<p>$$4^{3} = 64$$<\/p>\n\n<p>64 possible combinations. Of these 64, 61 <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNA_Codon_Table\">are words with a specific meaning<\/a> and 3, the STOP codons, are punctuation marks, full stops if you will. In other words, <strong>all possible combinations of letters have meaning in DNA<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Because all possible 3-letter combinations have meaning, no change will affect the information content of the \"sentence\". All it can do is change it. Now, changing the information can indeed result in \"sentences\" that make no sense. In the DNA world, this most often results in what are known as deleterious mutations. These happen all the time, but the result is usually a dead individual. Those with such mutations are not even born (speaking of mammals).<\/p>\n\n<p>However, other mutations, such as the change from <code>read<\/code> to <code>red<\/code> that I mentioned before, can give rise to a change of meaning, this change, if it turns out that it makes the individual carrying it more likely to reproduce, will spread across the population and will be <em>selected for<\/em>. That is how new traits can arise.<\/p>\n\n<p>In closing, another point that you have misunderstood is that evolution is not a path from the least to the most complex. In many ways it is the inverse. In fact, by any measure that counts, bacteria are <em>far<\/em> more \"evolved\" than humans for the very simple reason that the only way you can measure evolution is in terms of numbers of generations. Think of evolution as happening every time a species reproduces, this means that bacteria have had orders of magnitude more time to evolve than mammals have. Still, this is a useless comparison which is why nobody compares species by how \"evolved\" they are. For a discussion on that, have a look <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/q/832/1306\">here<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16119,"question_id":16106,"up_vote_count":11,"last_edit_date":1395913393},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bffd6b037fec5dba6e41dfd5c6b538d7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6137,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6137/displayname","reputation":267,"display_name":"DisplayName"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1395878421,"creation_date":1395878421,"body":"<p>evolution means unrolling <a href=\"http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=evolution\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=evolution<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Now if you imagine a tree with one root then the stem rolls out, branches roll out twigs and leaves roll out etc. Same with the roots on the other and to balance it out.<\/p>\n\n<p>And that's it. Evolution does not happen in a vacuum. It happens in and together with an environment. If the environment changes and you have unrolled something that helps you cope with that change then you can continue to procreate so that your offspring also have a chance to test any eventual new unrollings in the constantly changing environment. If they die then the branch or twig that was unrolled is cut off and might unroll again later and be cut off again until maybe, just maybe some sunlight will reach it and it can survive. Until night falls again.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16122,"question_id":16106,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bd4f0d39f82be9c22f6f01c80d7ad800?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6167,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6167/neil-slater","reputation":311,"display_name":"Neil Slater"},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a6fe697c4e898b884198a25103bb4f9e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6168,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6168/taemyr","reputation":101,"display_name":"Taemyr"},"score":0,"post_id":16131,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395912587,"comment_id":21703,"body":"+1 Short and to the point.  The other answers does a decent job of explaining evolution, but this answers OP&#39;s question."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/412efaafb7affe9c6667543f58de948c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5502,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5502/lotusbiology","reputation":38,"display_name":"LotusBiology"},"score":0,"post_id":16131,"edited":false,"creation_date":1396009315,"comment_id":21786,"body":"So what in the environment, tells the organism to make a new innovation like compound eyes, or superposition eyes? And again, what is Evolution&#39;s central processing unit. I.E. what physically deploys these new adaptations and abilities into the organism or population as a whole? Also, if you have the time, can you answer this video if you have a Youtube account. This is where I got these objections: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wf32BXMSN7A\" rel=\"nofollow\">youtube.com/watch?v=Wf32BXMSN7A<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bd4f0d39f82be9c22f6f01c80d7ad800?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6167,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6167/neil-slater","reputation":311,"display_name":"Neil Slater"},"score":0,"post_id":16131,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/412efaafb7affe9c6667543f58de948c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5502,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5502/lotusbiology","reputation":38,"display_name":"LotusBiology"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1396009690,"comment_id":21787,"body":"@LotusBiology: The pattern of light distribution is the information that &quot;tells&quot; the organism to create eyes (or more accurately rewards organisms that better sense light). The feasible and likely process from no eyes to complex eyes is well-studied, and indications are that this process has happened multiple times in the history of creatures. As for &quot;central processing unit&quot; there is no need for such a thing. Genes and proteins do not need a &quot;CPU&quot;"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/412efaafb7affe9c6667543f58de948c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5502,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5502/lotusbiology","reputation":38,"display_name":"LotusBiology"},"score":0,"post_id":16131,"edited":false,"creation_date":1396010878,"comment_id":21793,"body":"@NEIL SLATER Cool. If you have the time and a Youtube account, can you answer this video by Mark Champneys. This is where I got the crux of these questions: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wf32BXMSN7A\" rel=\"nofollow\">youtube.com/watch?v=Wf32BXMSN7A<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bd4f0d39f82be9c22f6f01c80d7ad800?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6167,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6167/neil-slater","reputation":311,"display_name":"Neil Slater"},"score":0,"post_id":16131,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/412efaafb7affe9c6667543f58de948c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5502,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5502/lotusbiology","reputation":38,"display_name":"LotusBiology"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1396011694,"comment_id":21794,"body":"@LotusBiology: In my opinion, the &quot;scientific objections&quot; raised in the video are actually a thin veil over desire for the end result (evolution being &quot;wrong&quot;). That is because it protects a cherished world view, and not due to any rigour in the arguments raised. Which means debating with someone who has published a video and has a lot of face to lose (and a lot of like-minded followers) is a waste of time. That&#39;s probably how you feel logging into biology.stackexchange and trying to challenge scientific consensus. But I have no desire to reciprocate."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1396013383,"creation_date":1395909187,"body":"<p><strong>Where does the information come from?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>From the environment, and the previous history of interactions in that environment. The process of evolution can be viewed as an undirected search for \"good\" solutions (i.e. those that better support replication) to problems presented by the environment.<\/p>\n\n<p>There is a large amount of information (in the information-theory sense) in a differentiated environment.<\/p>\n\n<p>Note that information content of the whole system <em>is<\/em> preserved when this happens. Partly the misunderstanding of \"information is being created\" is not seeing what a <strong>huge<\/strong> resource of information (in the same sense used with information theory that says it may not be created or destroyed) is available from the environment. It is many many orders of magnitude greater than anything stored in genetic codes.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16131,"question_id":16106,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1396013383},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb576b29171a8396bf8acdb680c7e08?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6165,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6165/mcv","reputation":121,"display_name":"mcv"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1395910067,"creation_date":1395910067,"body":"<blockquote>\n  <p>It is understood that Evolution basically involves three elements. Natural selection, genetic mutation, and time. The problem for Evolution, is that none of those three elements are creative.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>They absolutely are creative in that they create something new. Mutation introduces random errors, some of which may never have existed before in that combination of genes. Now <em>usually<\/em> errors are bad, and natural selection prunes the result, but every once in a while, you accidentally stumble upon something new that provides an advantage, and now natural selection means it gets kept and passed on to the next generation.<\/p>\n\n<p>So on their own, it might seem that mutation doesn't add information and natural selection doesn't create anything new, but together, natural selection adds information to the randomness of mutation: it selects what works and what doesn't.<\/p>\n\n<p>Imagine you're rolling a die <em>(warning! simplified analogies don't accurately reflect the complexities of evolution)<\/em>. What are the chances of you rolling 10 sixes in a row? Vanishingly small of course. But that's not what evolution does. What it does is in every phase (generation), it rolls 10 dice, and only keeps the sixes. What is the chance of getting a six in every phase now? Quite a lot bigger. All through randomness and selection.<\/p>\n\n<p>(In fact, have you ever played Yahtzee? How can you get the right patterns there if you're just rolling dice and selecting some of them?)<\/p>\n\n<p>Take your analogy with the sentence \"Make an eye that is compound\". A mutation might turn that into \"Make an eyye that is compound\" which is useless. But another mutation might turn it into \"Bake an eye that is compound\" which is grammatically correct though nonsensical. Yet another mutation might create \"Make an eyr that is compound\", and if that one happens to survive a generation, you might get \"Make an ear that is compound\".<\/p>\n\n<p>Thing is, there are a <em>lot<\/em> of mutations. Really a lot. Most of them have no measurable effect. Of the remainder, the vast majority breaks something, which means they automatically get weeded out by natural selection. A tiny fraction accidentally adds something useful. If you look at any single mutation, it's impossible to imagine how that could ever result in anything useful, but there's a lot of them. Every generation again, over thousands and millions of years, and eventually, those very few positive mutations start to add up.<\/p>\n\n<p>It's impossible to fully grasp how evolution can introduce totally new species without first grasping the enormous time scale on which evolution works. And we humans are limited beings and bad at truly understanding such enormous scales. But it clearly works. We can see the results all around us. We can run simulations on computers that show that the process really does work. I consider it one of God's greatest miracles <em>(warning! personal opinion might not reflect those of others)<\/em>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16132,"question_id":16106,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5940aefd57c6c8f7e9921d0512bc1d81?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6170,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6170/christian-sauer","reputation":111,"display_name":"Christian Sauer"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb576b29171a8396bf8acdb680c7e08?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6165,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6165/mcv","reputation":121,"display_name":"mcv"},"score":0,"post_id":16135,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395915280,"comment_id":21706,"body":"From bacteria to something with 4 legs <i>probably<\/i> close to zero? Just going from bacteria to single celled eukariotes took a billion years. That may have been the hardest and most fundamental step in our evolution. The chance of that happening in a single generation is as zero as quantum mechanics allows."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5940aefd57c6c8f7e9921d0512bc1d81?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6170,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6170/christian-sauer","reputation":111,"display_name":"Christian Sauer"},"score":0,"post_id":16135,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb576b29171a8396bf8acdb680c7e08?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6165,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6165/mcv","reputation":121,"display_name":"mcv"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1395915406,"comment_id":21707,"body":"@mcv That should qualify as close to zero ;) Acutally, the probabillity is even lower, because you need them twice (male and female), otherwise it will get lost at once."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/otBg3.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6151,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6151/richard-tingle","reputation":161,"display_name":"Richard Tingle"},"score":0,"post_id":16135,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395922593,"comment_id":21719,"body":"@ChristianSauer Male and female is somewhat of a specialisation of sexual reproduction, things can be simultaneously male and female or it can be N/A. Even bacteria have <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sexual_reproduction#Bacteria_and_archaea\" rel=\"nofollow\">sexual reproduction<\/a> without the concept of gender. In the presence of individuals who are mixedgender becoming purely male isn&#39;t a disadvantage"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1395912866,"creation_date":1395912866,"body":"<p>Another important point about evolution is, that rhere are many, many small steps - not huge leaps.\nE.g. going from a bacteria to something with four legs in one step will not happen - that is simply too much change at once, and it's probabillity is close to zero.\nBut small steps happen all the time - if we take your example with a cephalopod: Imagine that there are some individual cephalopods who have a harder skin. Without predatory pressure this is next to useless: the cephalopod are investing energy on something which brings no benefit. So they are less fit and will probably have fewer offspring than the original ones. Now a predator kill many soft-skinned cephalopods but sometimes fails to eat their harder skinned brethren. The hard-skin variant will producre more offspring and theier genes spread. Then the next round happens: cephalopods with the hard skin might have another mutation which hardens the shell even more - or the predators might get better teeth.\nBut be aware that this most not happen: maybe no variant with harder skin exists or the genetic error is not present at the time and the whole race simply dies - this happens a lot. Look at dinosaurs or the polar bear (is under pressure because the polar ice melts) etc.<\/p>\n\n<p>Some fun fact: since each step is random and has a low probabillity, you willl never get the same reult twice. If you start the evoluation again, the world would look completely different because the steps would look different.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16135,"question_id":16106,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16106/how-does-the-creative-process-of-biological-evolution-work","last_activity_date":1396013383,"creation_date":1395847525,"answer_count":8,"title":"How does the creative process of Biological Evolution work?","body":"<p>In order for nature to go from microbes to man, there needs to be new information. Where does this new information come from?<\/p>\n\n<p>It is understood that Evolution basically involves three elements. Natural selection, genetic mutation, and time. The problem for Evolution, is that none of those three elements are creative. Natural selection is basically just a pruning process. It selects from what is there and advantageous, and prunes off what is deleterious to the organism as far as its fitness. <\/p>\n\n<p>Genetic mutation is just errors in replication. So it creates nothing. It simply degrades. We have no new information, just an erroneous replication, and degradation of what was there before.<\/p>\n\n<p>That is still true of gene duplication. We have an error that repeats the same information/genes. So we have two copies of something but there is still no new information.<\/p>\n\n<p>This brings us to the second problem. What mechanism or process of nature/Evolution, carries out the instructions. What I mean by this, is that it essentially has to work like a computer. If I want my computer to have a more advanced program, I need to input new information, and its often codified in the form of say a disk, or installation file. <\/p>\n\n<p>What is the equivalent of this installation file for Evolution?<\/p>\n\n<p>For example. Say I'm a cephalopod. And I'm getting environmental pressure from predators and I want, or need, to advance my defenses, so I want to built some spikes on a hard outer shell. Where does the cephalopod get the new information, or rather, instructions, to know how to do this new feature? <\/p>\n","question_id":16106,"tags":["evolution"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":5,"protected_date":1395919969,"is_answered":true,"view_count":736,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1396011825},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a659be962c006e43e110b5a9dfda538e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3830,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3830/aerovistae","reputation":106,"display_name":"Aerovistae"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/07d542a58ef9867b4ac2309ecdac3d2e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3631,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3631/chinmay-kanchi","reputation":919,"display_name":"Chinmay Kanchi"},"score":0,"post_id":16146,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395938245,"comment_id":21738,"body":"You might find this interesting: <a href=\"http://royalsociety.org/events/2006/plagues-parasites/?gclid=CLD5yoOTs70CFedV4godnwUA1A#\" rel=\"nofollow\">royalsociety.org/events/2006/plagues-parasites/&hellip;<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/otBg3.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6151,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6151/richard-tingle","reputation":161,"display_name":"Richard Tingle"},"score":1,"post_id":16146,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395943185,"comment_id":21755,"body":"Evolution doesn&#39;t really work like that, everything is a slightly different version of what we had last year, it&#39;s only on the very long term that you can see major change. New flu arrives every year, but we still call it flu because it&#39;s only a little different"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cc86e1f443171a35a1c7dcf2c688f24c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6184,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.c