ttps://i.stack.imgur.com/RIrIa.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5922,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5922/playsdice","reputation":646,"display_name":"PlaysDice"},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":1,"post_id":16161,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395991513,"comment_id":21775,"body":"Adding to this: When using only one color to mark the sample, you can only use one sample (direct comparisions are not possible, since they can not be discriminated). The intensity of the signal here is used to measure the strength of expression, which can also cause some bias."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1395969464,"creation_date":1395969464,"body":"<p>Single channel refers to the system used to detect the labelled probes.  A single channel array, as shown in this <a href=\"http://faculty.ucr.edu/~tgirke/HTML_Presentations/Manuals/Microarray/arrayBasics.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">slidedeck<\/a> (slides 6-8) uses one type of molecule for detection.  In the example, (slide 8) the optical label is phycoerythrin.   Contrast that to a double channel array (e.g slide 7) that uses a \"green\" or \"red\" molecule used to label probes.  Detecting two different labels requires two channels, one to detect red and one the the green.   The key to using two (or more) labeling molecules is to ensure that your detection system can discriminate between the light spectrum emitted by each of the labels.   Many modern microarray readers have designs that handle multiple labels.<br>\nWhen you see single channel results, they often have colors.  The color is a pseudo color representation of the intensity of the emission of single-color label, which is due to how much probe has bound to the array at that spot. <\/p>\n","answer_id":16161,"question_id":16141,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16141/single-channel-micro-arrays","last_activity_date":1395969464,"creation_date":1395926160,"answer_count":1,"title":"Single channel micro arrays","body":"<p>What does single channel microarray mean?\nWhen is it used?\n Thank you for your case in advance.<\/p>\n","question_id":16141,"tags":["bioinformatics","microarray"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":16161,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":64,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user6116"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/RIrIa.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5922,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5922/playsdice","reputation":646,"display_name":"PlaysDice"},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1395953373,"creation_date":1395947795,"body":"<p>The answer is <em>it depends<\/em>.  First, take a step back from the definitions of \"cancer\" versus \"normal\" cell and recognize that cells and tissues can undergo a variety of changes in their growth.  A solid cancer/tumor (as its usually defined) is something that grows and invades the surrounding tissue.   A spectrum of possible cell growth can be :<\/p>\n\n<p>normal -> hypertrophy -> hyperplasia or dysplasia -> hamartoma -> benign tumor -> carcinoma in situ -> invasive cancer -> metastais<\/p>\n\n<p>(this list is <strong>NOT<\/strong> suggesting these are the actual steps to cancer, but instead they are useful for the next paragraph): <\/p>\n\n<p>The point of this list is that from a <em>human<\/em> perspective <strong>we<\/strong> can see something odd happening when we see a tumor, but the view from inside a cancer cell is basically \"things are fine, I'm just doing my cell thing\".  <\/p>\n\n<p>But, that said...when a tumor grows and cancer cells invade tissues a few things happen which can give rise to differences between cancer cells and normal tissues and which can be detected.<br>\nFirst, it needs energy, and cancer cells often switch to aerobic glycolysis (a phenomenon called the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warburg_effect#Oncology\" rel=\"nofollow\">Warburg effect<\/a>). As the link shows, a special form of labelled glucose can be used to detect this in the body.   <\/p>\n\n<p>Secondly, a tumor invades the surrounding tissue and generates new blood vessels, and so enzymes that break down <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proteases_in_angiogenesis\" rel=\"nofollow\">extracellular matrix <\/a> are released.   <\/p>\n\n<p>Some tumors over-express and secrete markers (usually proteins) that can be detected.  The <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prostate-specific_antigen\" rel=\"nofollow\">prostate specific antigen<\/a> (PSA) and <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carcinoembryonic_antigen\" rel=\"nofollow\">carcinoembryonic antigen<\/a> are two examples.   <\/p>\n\n<p>Other things secreted by certain tumors may <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canine_cancer_detection\" rel=\"nofollow\">include volatiles that can be detected by dogs<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>The challenge with any 'signature' detection is the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensitivity_and_specificity\" rel=\"nofollow\">sensitivity and specificity <\/a> which often limits the use of tests that show some early promise.<\/p>\n\n<p>Cancer cells <strong>DO<\/strong> have specific changes to their <a href=\"http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/understandingcancer/cancergenomics/AllPages\" rel=\"nofollow\">DNA<\/a> that can be used as very specific signatures for detection.  Tumor DNA is shed into the blood and possibly the urine.<\/p>\n\n<p>Finally, tumor biology overlaps with many aspects of normal biology, including wound healing and pregnancy and this continues to make it challenging to identify <em>tumor specific markers<\/em> that have high sensitivity and specificity.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16152,"question_id":16127,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1395953373}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16127/do-cancer-cells-give-off-specific-chemical-signatures","last_activity_date":1395953373,"creation_date":1395890075,"answer_count":1,"title":"Do cancer cells give off specific chemical signatures?","body":"<p>Do cancer cells give off specific chemical signatures?   Are these signatures different from normal cells?<\/p>\n","question_id":16127,"tags":["cancer"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":16152,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":168,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/525689ce2b6388ca2c525c89121a6ecd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5083,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5083/matt-thrower","reputation":328,"display_name":"Matt Thrower","accept_rate":50},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":1,"post_id":16117,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395867774,"comment_id":21650,"body":"In terms of cremation: Which remaining nutrients?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/525689ce2b6388ca2c525c89121a6ecd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5083,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5083/matt-thrower","reputation":328,"display_name":"Matt Thrower","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":16117,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1395868509,"comment_id":21652,"body":"No idea. I presumed that not everything in the human body was easily oxidized?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":0,"post_id":16117,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395868855,"comment_id":21653,"body":"Well, we are talking about 60-90 min (if I remember correctly) at temperatures of 900&#176;C. There nothing carbon based will survive. The remains are basically the mineral parts of the body."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":16117,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395927243,"comment_id":21723,"body":"Perhaps you can remove the word &quot;legal&quot; from the question. I think there is no law on how to deal with a corpse. Even if there is one it will not be universal."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/07d542a58ef9867b4ac2309ecdac3d2e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3631,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3631/chinmay-kanchi","reputation":919,"display_name":"Chinmay Kanchi"},"score":0,"post_id":16117,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395937974,"comment_id":21735,"body":"+1 for the weirdness of the title."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a2aa805700341eff65465e651d37ddf8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6178,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6178/amber","reputation":1,"display_name":"Amber"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1395935103,"creation_date":1395935103,"body":"<p>Well, with cremation comes also a lot of harmful gasses entering the atmosphere as well, and from your question, I'm assuming you're interested in eco-friendly alternatives.<\/p>\n\n<p>I've heard of organic embalming fluids, so it might be interesting to you to look into that. Also a lot of steel and cement go into a traditional burial; if you were to be buried in a plain pine box with no fancy coatings or finishings, that would certainly speed up decomposition. If you look at traditional Jewish burial customs, you may find a bit of what you're looking for.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16145,"question_id":16117,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/07d542a58ef9867b4ac2309ecdac3d2e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3631,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3631/chinmay-kanchi","reputation":919,"display_name":"Chinmay Kanchi"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1395937590,"creation_date":1395937590,"body":"<p>The <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parsi\" rel=\"nofollow\">Parsis<\/a> and other <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zoroastrianism\" rel=\"nofollow\">Zoroastrians<\/a> dispose of their dead in a so-called <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tower_of_Silence\" rel=\"nofollow\">Tower of Silence<\/a>, where the body is left on a raised platform to be eaten by scavengers, particularly birds such as vultures.<\/p>\n\n<p>This is possibly (probably?) the quickest way for nutrients to re-enter the wider ecosystem, as scavengers usually work a whole lot quicker than microbes.<\/p>\n\n<p>Tibetan tradition also contains a ritual known as the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sky_burial\" rel=\"nofollow\">Sky Burial<\/a>, which achieves the same sort of thing. The Tibetan version may be even quicker, as once the scavengers have stripped the body, the bones are ground into a paste along with flour and yak's milk/butter to be fed to a second round of scavenging birds.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16148,"question_id":16117,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16117/whats-the-fastest-legal-way-for-the-nutrients-in-a-dead-body-to-re-enter-the-ec","last_activity_date":1395937590,"creation_date":1395864358,"answer_count":2,"title":"What's the fastest legal way for the nutrients in a dead body to re-enter the ecosystem?","body":"<p>Apologies for weirdness.<\/p>\n\n<p>Of the various legal methods of disposing of a human corpse, which one ensures the nutrients which compose the body get back into the wider ecosystem the fastest?<\/p>\n\n<p>Unless I've overlooked something (which is likely) the answer would seem to boil down to:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>Burial, in which case soil microbes have relatively free access to the body but will initially restrict their nutrients to the sub-soil ecosystem.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Cremation, in which case most of the nutrients are converted into heat and light energy by the furnace, although this energy, and the remaining nutrients, are then made available to the wider environment much more rapidly.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","question_id":16117,"tags":["microbiology","ecology","decay"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":72,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1e5af4a99e16f69535435d4c7a568dd9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3647,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3647/gnerkus","reputation":125,"display_name":"gnerkus"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/07d542a58ef9867b4ac2309ecdac3d2e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3631,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3631/chinmay-kanchi","reputation":919,"display_name":"Chinmay Kanchi"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1e5af4a99e16f69535435d4c7a568dd9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3647,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3647/gner