://i.stack.imgur.com/D6KNy.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>The first show a DNA ring with the normal helix-coiling. The second show the supercoiling of the coiled ring molecule. Imagine a rubber band. This you can twist around its band axis to get the coiling and around its vertical axis to get the supercoiling.<\/p>\n\n<p>For linear DNA molecules, this looks like this (taken from <a href=\"http://apbrwww5.apsu.edu/thompsonj/Anatomy%20&amp;%20Physiology/2010/2010%20Exam%20Reviews/Exam%201%20Review/Ch02%20Nucleic%20Acids%20and%20ATP.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>):<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/KJ9wf.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n","answer_id":16134,"question_id":16133,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16133/understanding-dna-supercoiling","last_activity_date":1395912125,"creation_date":1395911480,"answer_count":1,"title":"Understanding DNA supercoiling","body":"<p>While trying to understand DNA supercoiling, I came across these lines in the book <em>Genetics by Ursula Goodenough<\/em> :<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>All natural DNA is superhelical. The axis of the duplex itself follows\n  a helical path in space. For virtually all DNA, the sense of the\n  superhelical turns is opposite to that of duplex, thereofer, they are\n  negative supertwists.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>I am unable to understand these lines. Specially, the second one.<\/p>\n","question_id":16133,"tags":["genetics","dna","molecular-genetics"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":16134,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":345,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0a261867e5f2cf5d316c8de5f5c803b9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5460,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5460/apothemcyte","reputation":31,"display_name":"ApothemCyte","accept_rate":17},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0a261867e5f2cf5d316c8de5f5c803b9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5460,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5460/apothemcyte","reputation":31,"display_name":"ApothemCyte","accept_rate":17},"score":0,"post_id":16130,"edited":false,"creation_date":1396497724,"comment_id":22003,"body":"Thank you :) This helped a lot!"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1395909120,"creation_date":1395909120,"body":"<p><strong>Question a<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>The only possible genotype that brings a phenotype of 12 inches is: $AABBCC$. Similarly the only possible genotype that bring a phenotype of 6 inches is: $aabbcc$. In consequence the offsprings can only be: $AaBbCc$ which measure $2+1+2+1+2+1 = 9$ inches.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p><strong>Question b<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Now the question is: if we breed two $AaBbCc$ how many offsprings measure 11 inches? Because there are three bi-allelic genotypes you have $2^3=8$ possible gametes and therefore you have to draw a 8x8 punnett square. Doing so, just count the proportion of offsprings that measure 11 inches. You can reason slightly more logically and get a faster answer. To measure 11 inches you need to have only capital letters in your genome except at one position. In consequence, if your father gives the gamete $ABC$, you mother should give the gamete $ABc$, $AbC$ or $aBC$. You can inverse the role of the father and the mother and it works as well. Therefore, you have 6 possible combinations that give rise to an offspring that measure 11 inches. Because there are $8 \\cdot 8 = 64$ possible combinations, the proportion of offspring that are 11 inch-long is $\\frac{6}{64} = \\frac{3}{32} = 0.09375 ‚âà 0.1$. About 10% of your F2 individuals are 11 inch long.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":16130,"question_id":16126,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16126/quantitative-traits-genetics","last_activity_date":1395909120,"creation_date":1395888885,"answer_count":1,"title":"Quantitative Traits Genetics","body":"<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/IiBSG.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Can someone please help with this question? I'm not so sure whether part A should be 11 inches or something else. Also, is part B correct <\/p>\n","question_id":16126,"tags":["genetics","homework","gene-expression","allele","population-genetics"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":16130,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":75,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/anIxF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3657,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3657/katz","reputation":424,"display_name":"Katz","accept_rate":70},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":0,"post_id":16116,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395861132,"comment_id":21638,"body":"What do you mean by &quot;raw fold&quot;? Values not normalized to the normalization gene?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/anIxF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3657,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3657/katz","reputation":424,"display_name":"Katz","accept_rate":70},"score":0,"post_id":16116,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"