 else."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":0,"post_id":16096,"edited":false,"creation_date":1395851482,"comment_id":21625,"body":"Good point, i added this to the answer."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1395851478,"creation_date":1395839447,"body":"<p>A lot of enzymes need metal ion in their active center (it is actually the metal ion which is taking part in the catalyzed reaction). These are manganese, magnesium, copper and so on. For DNAses the metal in the active center is magnesium and EDTA simply chelates this ions, making them unavailable for the enzyme and thus hinders the enzyme from working.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chelation\" rel=\"nofollow\">Chelation<\/a> is the process in which metal ions are coordinated in molecules and form coordinate bonds to the chelating agent. <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethylenediaminetetraacetic_acid\" rel=\"nofollow\">EDTA<\/a> looks like this:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/JWM81.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>The 3d structure while chelating a metal ions like this:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/CiVsN.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>You can see, that the metal ion is nicely located between the negatively charged oxygen atoms and the nitrogen atoms. These complexes are fairly stable and the metal ions do not escape.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16096,"question_id":16093,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1395851478},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/VmtoK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1320,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1320/alan-boyd","reputation":17240,"display_name":"Alan Boyd"},"score":4,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count