ns<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Beaks:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Found in birds<\/li>\n<li>Feeding<\/li>\n<li>Defense<\/li>\n<li>Manipulation of objects<\/li>\n<li>Communication<\/li>\n<li>Heat exchange<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":9471,"question_id":9467,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bffd6b037fec5dba6e41dfd5c6b538d7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6137,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6137/displayname","reputation":267,"display_name":"DisplayName"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1395824725,"creation_date":1395824725,"body":"<p>What is a lip(s)? A set of muscles around an orifice that can close said orifice. <\/p>\n\n<p>How about a way to close a hole so that not everything can get in but what we want - to eat, breathe, drink?<\/p>\n\n<p>The fact that they are also sensitive is just needed so that you can more precisely operate them for whatever need you have.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16089,"question_id":9467,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/9467/what-use-a-pair-of-lips","last_activity_date":1395824725,"creation_date":1374923883,"answer_count":2,"title":"What use a pair of lips?","body":"<p>Pardon my ignorance ... A lip is apparently a very sensitive tactile device - as it at-least serves to warn it's owner they may just be about to consume something that could cause injury. Primates (including humans), dogs, cats, sheep, buffalo, elephants, some fish, octopodes - to name a few, have a lip. <\/p>\n\n<p>How have lips evolved to be nearly ubiquitous across animals? Why have they evolved into a beak/bill in some birds &amp; fish? What niche/purpose do they fulfill?<\/p>\n","question_id":9467,"tags":["physiology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":192,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user6116"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/av